1092.meaning: Four control knobs, as adjust audio levels on a mixing console. Generally depicted as a silver square with black knobs, turned to various levels as indicated by white pointers and scale markings.

1093.name: Radio
1093.meaning: A classic portable radio, as used to listen to music, news, or sports. Depicted in various colors and styles with a speaker, antenna, dial, and knobs.

1094.name: Banjo
1094.meaning: A banjo with a round body and a long neck. Used to talk about banjos or music in general.

1095.name: Mobile Phone
1095.meaning: A mobile phone (cell phone), as used to text, check social media, or take selfies. Depicted as a black or gray smartphone with a generic blue screen or multicolored app icons. Commonly used for various content concerning mobile phones, technology, and communication.

1096.name: Mobile Phone with Arrow
1096.meaning: A mobile phone (cell phone) with a rightward arrow pointed at it from the left. Intended to indicate an incoming call or message, but used to represent mobile phones, technology, and communication more generally.

1097.name: Telephone
1097.meaning: A classic telephone, as a landline home phone. Most platforms depict a red, push-button phone with the handset on the base. Some platforms feature designs with rotary dials.

1098.name: Telephone Receiver
1098.meaning: The handset of a traditional telephone, with speaker and microphone. Generally depicted in black at a 45° angle.

1099.name: Pager
1099.meaning: A pager, as worn on the waist to alert a person to a phone call or short text message. Popular in the 1980–90s before mobile phones, though still used by some medical and emergency personnel. Very occasionally used to represent alerts, digital communication, or nostalgia for old technology.

1100.name: Fax Machine
1100.meaning: A fax machine, as scans and transmits documents over a telephone line. Common in the 1980–90s before the internet. Depicted as a white or black machine with a telephone handset, keypad, display screen, and paper in its tray.

1101.name: Battery
1101.meaning: An electric battery, as used to power such devices as a flashlight. Generally depicted as an upright, green cylinder, as a AA or D cell, with white indicators for its positive (facing up) and negative terminals.

1102.name: Electric Plug
1102.meaning: An electric plug, as inserted into socket to power a device. Depicted as a black, two-pronged plug at various angles at the end of a cable. Prongs are silver or gold.

1103.name: Laptop
1103.meaning: A laptop personal computer. Depicted as a black or gray device, opened to show a dark or blue screen, keyboard, and touchpad.

1104.name: Desktop Computer
1104.meaning: A desktop personal computer. Generally depicted as a black or gray monitor with a dark or blue screen.

1105.name: Printer
1105.meaning: A computer printer, as at a home office. Generally depicted as a grayish device with a power button and paper loaded in its tray, sometimes printing out a document. May be used for various content concerning printing, including as a Print icon, as well as for office work and technology more generally.

1106.name: Keyboard
1106.meaning: A keyboard, as used to type on a computer. Generally depicted as a gray device with white or black keys. Used for various content concerning computers, typing, and writing.

1107.name: Computer Mouse
1107.meaning: A mouse, as used to control a cursor on a computer. Generally depicted as a white or gray, cordless device with a scroll wheel between left- and right-click buttons.

1108.name: Trackball
1108.meaning: A trackball, as rotated to control a cursor on a computer. An alternative or supplement to a computer mouse or touchpad. Generally depicted as a cordless device with a blue or red ball in a cylindrical, black or gray socket.

1109.name: Computer Disk
1109.meaning: A minidisc, depicted as a small, silver or gold optical disc housed in a square cartridge, its shutter positioned to the right.

1110.name: Floppy Disk
1110.meaning: A 3.5-inch floppy disk, a data storage format popular in the 1980–90s but largely preserved as a Save icon in computer programs. Shown with its silver shutter positioned up and in a black housing with a white label, accented with blue or red.

1111.name: Optical Disk
1111.meaning: A silver optical disc, as a CD or DVD, used to play music or movies before the rise of streaming technology. Commonly used to represent CDs, DVDs, Blu-rays, and related film and music content, especially albums.

1112.name: DVD
1112.meaning: A digital versatile disc (DVD), a type of optical disc used to play movies before the rise of streaming technology. Generally depicted in gold, though Facebook’s is bluish gray, as a Blu-ray.

1113.name: Abacus
1113.meaning: An abacus, an ancient tool used to count and calculate by moving beads. Depicted as a wooden frame with four or more rows or columns of variously positioned and colored beads.

1114.name: Movie Camera
1114.meaning: A classic movie camera. Depicted as a black camera with two mounted reels of film, viewfinder, and lens pointed left or right.

1115.name: Film Frames
1115.meaning: A strip of film, as used in a movie camera or photography. Generally depicted as several horizontal frames of unexposed film with black trim and perforations.

1116.name: Film Projector
1116.meaning: A classic film projector, as projects film onto a screen for viewing. Generally depicted as a black or gray projector with two mounted reels and lens pointed right.

1117.name: Television
1117.meaning: A classic television set, as people watched before streaming on flatscreens. Depicted in various colors and styles with a screen, knobs, and, on many platforms, rabbit-ear antennae.

1118.name: Camera
1118.meaning: A classic camera, as an SLR used to take pictures before camera phones. Generally depicted with a black and silver casing with lens and operating controls.

1119.name: Camera with Flash
1119.meaning: A classic camera, shown with its flash going off, as to illuminate a darker scene. Vendors implement the same design as 📷 Camera with a burst of light, often resembling 💥 Collision.

1120.name: Video Camera
1120.meaning: A video camera, as a camcorder used to film home videos in the 1980–90s. Generally depicted as a gray or black video camera with viewfinder, control buttons, and lens pointed left.

1121.name: Videocassette
1121.meaning: A videotape cassette, as a VHS tape used to watch movies or record TV on VCRs before DVDs , DVRs, and streaming. Generally depicted as a black cassette with a white label between its reels.

1122.name: Magnifying Glass Tilted Left
1122.meaning: A classic magnifying glass, as used to view small objects, with its lens pointed left. Generally depicted at a 45° angle with a black handle and a clear or blue, silver-framed lens titled to the upper left.

1123.name: Magnifying Glass Tilted Right
1123.meaning: A classic magnifying glass, as used to view small objects, with its lens pointed right. Generally depicted at a 45° angle with a black handle and a clear or blue, silver-framed lens titled to the upper right.

1124.name: Candle
1124.meaning: A burning candle, as lit when taking a bath or the power is out. Depicted as a white, pillar-shaped candle with a flame and wax dripping down its sides.

1125.name: Light Bulb
1125.meaning: A light bulb, as screwed into a lamp to light a room. Depicted as an incandescent bulb with a silver base, often shown with filament and a soft, yellow-white glow.

1126.name: Flashlight
1126.meaning: An everyday flashlight (electric torch), as used when the power goes out, camping, or telling scary stories. Generally depicted at a 45° angle as a gray and black device with a switch, shown illuminated on many platforms.

1127.name: Red Paper Lantern
1127.meaning: A red paper lantern, as hangs outside an izakaya, a Japanese bar that serves drinks and casual food. Generally depicted as cylindrical with a black top and base and soft, orange glow.

1128.name: Diya Lamp
1128.meaning: A lamp made of brass or clay, displayed with a lit wick leading into oil or ghee.

1129.name: Notebook with Decorative Cover
1129.meaning: A closed, hardcover notebook, as used for journaling or sketching. Appearance varies across platforms, with most designs featuring relatively plain covers. Commonly used for content concerning writing and schooling.

1130.name: Closed Book
1130.meaning: A closed, hardcover book depicted with a red cover on most platforms. Commonly used for various content concerning reading, writing, learning, and schooling. May also be used as a red accent color.

1131.name: Open Book
1131.meaning: An open, hardcover book, depicted with a blue cover on most platforms. Some platforms include a bookmark. Commonly used for various content concerning reading, writing, learning, and schooling.

1132.name: Green Book
1132.meaning: A closed, green, hardcover book. Commonly used for various content concerning reading, writing, learning, and schooling. May also be used as a green accent color.

1133.name: Blue Book
1133.meaning: A closed, blue, hardcover book. Commonly used for various content concerning reading, writing, learning, and schooling. May also be used as a blue accent color.

1134.name: Orange Book
1134.meaning: A closed, orange, hardcover book—similar to the Emojipedia logo 📙😃. Commonly used for various content concerning reading, writing, learning, and schooling. May also be used as an orange accent color.

1135.name: Books
1135.meaning: A loose stack of three of more different-colored, hardcover books. Commonly used for various content concerning reading and schooling. Color and orientation vary across platforms, but often shown with red, green, and blue covers.

1136.name: Notebook
1136.meaning: A dark-colored, hardcover notebook, as used to write or take notes in school. Commonly used for various content concerning writing and schooling.

1137.name: Ledger
1137.meaning: A spiral-bound, yellow, hardcover notebook. Intended to depict a financial ledger, as used in accounting.

1138.name: Page with Curl
1138.meaning: A white piece of paper, curled up at the bottom to the left or right, with text printed on it, as a business letter. Commonly used for content concerning various types of documents and writing.

1139.name: Scroll
1139.meaning: An ancient scroll, unrolled to reveal text on papyrus or parchment paper. May be used to represent the study of history or official documents, such as a diploma.

1140.name: Page Facing Up
1140.meaning: A white piece of paper, its top right corner curled or dog-eared, with text printed on it, as a business letter or icon for a document on a computer. Commonly used for content concerning various types of documents and writing.

1141.name: Newspaper
1141.meaning: The front page of a newspaper, as people once read the news before the internet. Commonly used for various content concerning news, media, and journalism as well as personal news.

1142.name: Rolled-Up Newspaper
1142.meaning: A newspaper rolled up and bound, as for delivery to a house. Generally positioned at a 45° angle. Commonly used for various content concerning news, media, and journalism as well as personal news.

1143.name: Bookmark Tabs
1143.meaning: Sheets of white, printed paper with variously colored tabs to bookmark important sections or indicate signature lines. Commonly used for content concerning various types of documents and writing.

1144.name: Bookmark
1144.meaning: A bookmark, as used to mark one's place in a book. May also represent bookmarks on an internet browser. Appearance varies across platforms, but generally depicted at a 45° angle as a thin, white or red strip with a decorative tie and design, such as flower or star.

1145.name: Label
1145.meaning: A light-brown or yellow rectangular tag, as labelled and attached to a key. Depicted at various angles punched with a hole, generally with a metal ring or loop of string.

1146.name: Money Bag
1146.meaning: A bag full of money. Depicted as a sack, usually tan, tied off and displaying a dollar sign. May be filled with coins, as most platforms show a rounded bag.

1147.name: Coin
1147.meaning: A coin, shown in silver or gold. Appearance varies by platform, with Google and Twitter showing a 🏛️ Classical Building, while Samsung shows the number one, similar to a 🥇 1st Place Medal.

1148.name: Yen Banknote
1148.meaning: A banded stack of yen banknotes, the paper currency of Japan. Color and detail vary across platforms, but usually shown in green, yellow, or pink with the yen symbol, ¥. Commonly used for various content concerning money and wealth, not restricted to Japan.

1149.name: Dollar Banknote
1149.meaning: Cash money! A banded stack of U.S. dollar banknotes, the paper currency of the United States of America. Green hue and detail vary across platforms, but shown with the dollar sign, $. Commonly used for various content concerning wealth and money, not restricted to the U.S.

1150.name: Euro Banknote
1150.meaning: A banded stack of euro banknotes, the paper currency of the European Union (EU). Color and detail vary across platforms, but shown with the euro sign, €. Commonly used for various content concerning wealth and money, not restricted to the EU.

1151.name: Pound Banknote
1151.meaning: Quids in! A banded stack of pound banknotes, the paper currency of the United Kingdom (England, Wales, Northern Ireland, and Scotland). Color and detail vary across platforms, but widely depicted as purple £20 notes with the pound sign, £.

1152.name: Money with Wings
1152.meaning: A banded stack of U.S. dollar bills with feather wings, as if flying. Its flight may represent losing, transferring, or earning money, but commonly used for wealth, money, and success more generally, often with a flourish or sense of flair.

1153.name: Credit Card
1153.meaning: The backside of a credit card, showing the magnetic strip and signature. Color and detail vary across platforms, but often shown as gold, silver, or blue. May be used for banking and other ID cards as well for various content concerning money, including payment.

1154.name: Receipt
1154.meaning: A white paper receipt, as proof of payment, and shown flat or curled. May be used for other financial documents (e.g., invoice, tax form). May also be used for the slang receipts, or "evidence” or “confirmation” of some feat or controversy.

1155.name: Envelope
1155.meaning: The back of an envelope, as used to send a letter or card in the mail (post). Generally depicted in white, though Google’s design is yellow. Used for various content concerning mail and messages, including email.

1156.name: E-Mail
1156.meaning: A symbol for email. Depicted as the back of an envelope imprinted with a capital letter E (for electronic) or @ (at) sign. Commonly used as an icon before an email address.

1157.name: Incoming Envelope
1157.meaning: The back of an envelope, shown coming into an inbox or arriving with motion lines.

1158.name: Envelope with Arrow
1158.meaning: The back of envelope with a down arrow on top. Generally depicted in white (except for Google’s yellow design) with a red or blue arrow.

1159.name: Outbox Tray
1159.meaning: A paper tray with an up arrow on top, as a symbol for an email outbox. Generally depicted as a white or wooden tray with a red arrow.

1160.name: Inbox Tray
1160.meaning: A paper tray with a down arrow on top, as a symbol for an email inbox. Generally depicted as a white or wooden try with a red or green arrow.

1161.name: Package
1161.meaning: A package (parcel), as contains items ordered online. Depicted at various angles as a light-brown, cardboard box, with a shipping label and its top taped shut.

1162.name: Closed Mailbox with Raised Flag
1162.meaning: A curbside mailbox (letterbox, postbox) with its door latched shut and signal flag raised. Generally depicted in blue or gray with a red flag. Used for various content concerning postal deliveries and email.

1163.name: Closed Mailbox with Lowered Flag
1163.meaning: A curbside mailbox (letterbox, postbox) with its door latched shut and signal flag lowered. Generally depicted in blue or gray with a red flag. Used for various content concerning postal deliveries and email.

1164.name: Open Mailbox with Raised Flag
1164.meaning: An open, curbside mailbox (letterbox, postbox) with its signal flag raised and a letter in its open slot. Generally depicted in blue or gray with a red flag and white envelope (Google's design is yellow). Used for various content concerning postal deliveries and email.

1165.name: Open Mailbox with Lowered Flag
1165.meaning: A curbside mailbox (letterbox, postbox) with its signal flag lowered and its slot empty. Generally depicted in blue or gray with a red flag. Used for various content concerning postal deliveries and email.

1166.name: Postbox
1166.meaning: A postbox (mailbox, letterbox) with a letter in its slot for collection. Generally depicted in red with a white envelope, styled after public postboxes in Japan. May also evoke postboxes in the United Kingdom.

1167.name: Ballot Box with Ballot
1167.meaning: A ballot box, as used to cast votes in an election. Depicted as a box, generally blue or gray, with a slot on top through which a paper ballot is being inserted. Many platforms display a cross mark or check mark on the ballot to indicate a vote, though Apple and Facebook leave theirs blank.

1168.name: Pencil
1168.meaning: A classic yellow pencil. Depicted as a graphite pencil, like a U.S. #2 or European HB, with a sharpened tip and pink eraser. Positioned at a 45° angle, with its tip at the lower left or right. Commonly used for various content concerning writing, drawing, and schooling.

1169.name: Black Nib
1169.meaning: The silver nib of a fountain pen, which distributes ink onto a writing surface. Positioned at a 45° angle, with its tip at the lower left or right. Like 🖋️ Fountain Pen, commonly used for various content concerning writing, drawing, and signing (e.g., laws, deals, in sports).

1170.name: Fountain Pen
1170.meaning: A black fountain pen with a silver nib, as used for signing important documents. Often depicted with gold hardware. Positioned at a 45° angle with its tip at the lower left. Like ✒️ Black Nib, commonly used for various content concerning writing, drawing, and signing (e.g., laws, deals, in sports).

1171.name: Pen
1171.meaning: A blue or black ballpoint pen, as used for everyday writing. Depicted with its cap removed onto its end or as retractable pen. Positioned at a 45° angle, its tip at the lower left. Commonly used for various content concerning writing (e.g., creative, professional) as well as signing (deals, laws, in sports).

1172.name: Paintbrush
1172.meaning: A thin, artist's paintbrush, as used to paint a picture. Often depicted with reddish paint on its pointed bristles. Positioned at a 45° angle, its tip at the lower left.

1173.name: Crayon
1173.meaning: A crayon, as children use to color. Depicted as red on most platforms with two black stripes on its label, resembling a Crayola crayon. Positioned at a 45° angle, its tip at the lower left. Commonly used for various content concerning drawing, colors, arts and crafts, and schooling.

1174.name: Memo
1174.meaning: A white piece of paper with text written on it by a yellow pencil, positioned over the sheet, tip down, at a 45° angle. Commonly used for content concerning various types of documents and writing, including signing (in sports).

1175.name: File Folder
1175.meaning: A tabbed folder, as used to file papers in a cabinet or as an icon for a file on a computer. Most platforms depict a yellow folder, as manila, with the tab shown at the left.

1176.name: Open File Folder
1176.meaning: A slightly open tabbed folder, as used to file papers in a cabinet or as an icon for an opened folder when using a computer. Most platforms depict a yellow folder, as manila, with the tab shown at the left.

1177.name: Card Index Dividers
1177.meaning: A set of tabbed dividers or file guides, as used to organize a card index or file box. Depicted with three or more multicolored tabs on manila paper.

1178.name: Calendar
1178.meaning: A single date on a calendar. Generally depicted as a page torn off from a daily desk calendar, displaying month and day on a white, square page.

1179.name: Tear-Off Calendar
1179.meaning: A single date on a calendar. Generally depicted as a page on a two-ringed, daily desk calendar, as flipped or torn off to change the date. Displays month and day on a white, square page, curled up at the bottom right.

1180.name: Spiral Notepad
1180.meaning: A spiral-bound, flip-style notepad or notebook of lined paper, as used for everyday note-taking. Commonly used for content concerning various types of documents and writing.

1181.name: Spiral Calendar
1181.meaning: A spiral-bound calendar. Generally depicted as a monthly calendar, with a red or blue header. Apple and Samsung’s pages are curled up at the bottom right, as to flip for a new month.

1182.name: Card Index
1182.meaning: A card index, as a Rolodex, once used to organize and access cards containing the information of personal or business contacts. Depicted as a black or gray rotating device with a contact card displayed, including a graphic and text.

1183.name: Chart Increasing
1183.meaning: A graph showing a red (or sometimes green) trend line increasing over time, as stock prices or revenues. Commonly used to represent various types of increase, from numerical data to being metaphorically on the rise. May also represent trending content as well as facts, figures, and charts more generally.

1184.name: Chart Decreasing
1184.meaning: A graph showing a colored trend line, often blue, decreasing over time, as stock prices or revenues. Commonly used to represent various types of decrease, from numeral data to being metaphorically down. May also represent facts, figures, and charts more generally.

1185.name: Bar Chart
1185.meaning: A bar graph generally showing three different-colored, vertical rectangles at various heights, as compares values across a category. Commonly used to represent various types of data, information, facts, figures, and charts more generally.

1186.name: Clipboard
1186.meaning: A white piece of paper secured by a silver clip on a brown clipboard, as used as a writing surface when standing. Commonly used for content concerning various types of documents and writing, especially in sports.

1187.name: Pushpin
1187.meaning: A thumbtack (drawing pin), as used to pin documents on a bulletin (notice) board. Depicted at a 45° angle with its red, flat head to the upper right.

1188.name: Round Pushpin
1188.meaning: A pushpin, as used to indicate a location on a map. Generally depicted as an upright pin with a red, round head.

1189.name: Paperclip
1189.meaning: A silver paper clip, as used to hold together sheets of paper—or remove a SIM card from a mobile phone. Shown positioned at various angles.

1190.name: Linked Paperclips
1190.meaning: Two or more silver paper clips linked together, generally forming an inverted V. Microsoft’s design displays three paper clips.

1191.name: Straight Ruler
1191.meaning: A ruler, as used to draw straight lines and measure distances. Variously depicted as a metal, wood, or plastic straightedge with length markings at a 45° angle.

1192.name: Triangular Ruler
1192.meaning: A triangle or set square, as used by engineers or architects to draw straight lines at angles. Variously depicted as a metal, wood, or plastic right triangle with length markings, its hypotenuse to the right.

1193.name: Scissors
1193.meaning: A pair of scissors, as used to cut paper or hair. Generally shown open, blades down, with red handles. Commonly used for content concerning haircuts, fashion design, arts and crafts, and various senses of cutting.

1194.name: Card File Box
1194.meaning: A black or gray box with a label holder, containing card index dividers with multicolored tabs, as used to organize and store files. Apple and Facebook’s designs include a lid.

1195.name: File Cabinet
1195.meaning: A metal filing cabinet, as used to organize and store file folders at an office. Depicted in black or gray with two drawers, handles, and label holders.

1196.name: Wastebasket
1196.meaning: A wastebasket, as used to discard trash in an office. Generally depicted as a silver, wire-mesh container. Also known as a wastepaper basket, trash/garbage can, or rubbish bin.

1197.name: Locked
1197.meaning: A locked (closed) padlock, as used to secure a latch or chain, or as an icon for a secure internet connection, private account, or locked device. Generally depicted with a gold base and silver shackle. WhatsApp’s design is silver.

1198.name: Unlocked
1198.meaning: An unlocked padlock, as used to secure a latch or chain, or as an icon for a non-secure connection or open access online. Generally depicted with a gold base and silver shackle, as an open 🔒 Locked.

1199.name: Locked with Pen
1199.meaning: A locked (closed) padlock with a fountain pen or nib positioned at various angles in front of it. Vendors implement the same design as their 🔒 Locked and the same or similar design as their 🖋️ Fountain Pen or ✒️ Black Nib.

1200.name: Locked with Key
1200.meaning: A locked (closed) padlock with an upright key at its right. Vendors implement the same designs as their 🔒 Locked and 🔑 Key.

1201.name: Key
1201.meaning: A key, as opens a door or lock. Depicted at a 45° angle as a gold, bronze, or copper key with a round head and notched blade. Commonly used for figurative senses of key, e.g., the key to success, being key ("crucial").

1202.name: Old Key
1202.meaning: An old-fashioned key, as opens an antique chest or wardrobe. Generally depicted at a 45° angle as a tarnished, silver skeleton key with an ornate, bowed head and two-toothed bit at the bottom left.

1203.name: Hammer
1203.meaning: A claw hammer, as used for driving or removing nails. Generally depicted with a metal head and wooden handle, positioned at a 45° angle with the head at the upper left.

1204.name: Axe
1204.meaning: An axe with a wooden handle and a metal blade. On many platforms the blade is red, like a fire axe.

1205.name: Pick
1205.meaning: A pickaxe, a tool with a curved spike for breaking up rocks in mining. Generally depicted with a metal head and wooden handle, positioned at a 45° angle with the head at the upper left.

1206.name: Hammer and Pick
1206.meaning: A hammer and pick, as used for breaking up rocks in mining, crossed in an X shape. Generally depicted as metal, mallet- and chisel-styled hammers with wooden handles. The heads of the tools face up, with the pick usually at the right. Often used for various content concerning tools, building, and construction.

1207.name: Hammer and Wrench
1207.meaning: A hammer and wrench, as kept in a toolbox, crossed in an X shape. Depicted with metal tools facing up, the hammer positioned at the upper left. Most vendors implement the same design as for their 🔨 Hammer and 🔧 Wrench.

1208.name: Dagger
1208.meaning: A pointed knife with a steel blade, as used for thrusting in close combat. Generally depicted as double-edged with a brown or black, cross-shaped hilt and positioned at 45° angle, often with its tip at the lower left.

1209.name: Crossed Swords
1209.meaning: Two swords with steel blades in an X shape, as crossed for combat between two knights or warriors. Generally depicted as straight, double-edged blades with brown or black, cross-shaped hilts, points directed up. Commonly used as a symbol for battle, fighting, or a contest, as in sports.

1210.name: Pistol
1210.meaning: A squirt gun (water pistol), as used to spray water for fun.

1211.name: Boomerang
1211.meaning:
Boomerang was approved as part of Unicode 13.0 in 2020
and added to Emoji 13.0 in 2020.

1212.name: Shield
1212.meaning: A shield, as blocks swords in close combat. Color and style varies across platforms, but generally depicted in a kite shape with a metal border and simple pattern.

1213.name: Carpentry Saw
1213.meaning:
Carpentry Saw was approved as part of Unicode 13.0 in 2020
and added to Emoji 13.0 in 2020.

1214.name: Wrench
1214.meaning: A metal wrench (spanner), as used for turning nuts and bolts. Depicted with two open, crescent-shaped ends or one open end and a closed, ring-shaped end. Generally positioned at a 45° angle.

1215.name: Screwdriver
1215.meaning:
Screwdriver was approved as part of Unicode 13.0 in 2020
and added to Emoji 13.0 in 2020.

1216.name: Nut and Bolt
1216.meaning: A metal bolt with a nut threaded around it, as by a wrench. Often positioned at a 45° angle, the head of the bolt at the upper left. Commonly used for various content concerning tools, building, and construction. May also be used for other hardware, including screws.

1217.name: Gear
1217.meaning: A round metal gear with teeth.

1218.name: Clamp
1218.meaning: A metal clamp or vice, as screwed to hold or compress materials like wood or metal. Depicted as a C-clamp or F-clamp, its screw in various positions.

1219.name: Balance Scale
1219.meaning: A balance scale, as historically used to measure weight. A symbol of justice, as held by Lady Justice, and of the zodiac sign of Libra, the Scales. Depicted as two silver or gold pans suspended from a beam and supported on a base.

1220.name: White Cane
1220.meaning: A white cane, used by some people who are blind or visually impaired. The cane has a black or gray handle with a wrist loop, a white middle section, and a red end with a white cap. This cane differs from a support cane and is sometimes called a probing cane.

1221.name: Link
1221.meaning: Two links of a silver chain, positioned at a 45° angle. Used as an icon for a hyperlink on computers and the internet. May also be used for metaphorical connections.

1222.name: Chains
1222.meaning: Two parallel lengths of silver chain. Occasionally used as an icon before a hyperlink or for metaphorical connections or chains, e.g., slang off the chains.

1223.name: Hook
1223.meaning:
Hook was approved as part of Unicode 13.0 in 2020
and added to Emoji 13.0 in 2020.

1224.name: Toolbox
1224.meaning: A red box for holding and transporting tools, such as a hammer and wrench. Generally depicted as latched shut with silver hardware and a black handle.

1225.name: Magnet
1225.meaning: A horseshoe magnet, as used to pick up iron. Depicted at various angles in red with silver-tipped poles.

1226.name: Ladder
1226.meaning:
Ladder was approved as part of Unicode 13.0 in 2020
and added to Emoji 13.0 in 2020.

1227.name: Alembic
1227.meaning: An apparatus for distilling, as used in medieval alchemy. Generally depicted as a round flask with a neck angled down to the right. Positioned on a short stand and containing a mysterious green, purple, or blue liquid.

1228.name: Test Tube
1228.meaning: A test tube, as used to conduct chemical experiments in a laboratory. Depicted as a clear cylinder, open at one end and containing a green liquid. Positioned at a 45° angle.

1229.name: Petri Dish
1229.meaning: A petri dish, as used to culture microbes. Depicted as a clear, shallow cylinder with a red, blue, or green growth medium, such as agar, with splotches of variously colored cells, like bacteria.

1230.name: DNA
1230.meaning: The double helix of DNA, the genetic blueprint for life. Color and orientation vary across platforms, but positioned at a 45° angle and in multiple, bright colors to represent the molecule’s spiraling, ladder-like structure.

1231.name: Microscope
1231.meaning: A microscope, as used in science laboratories to magnify small objects, such as cells or insects. Depicted as a compound opitical microscope with an adjustable eyepiece, lens, arm, and slide stage mounted on a base. Generally shown as metal with the viewing apparatus facing left.

1232.name: Telescope
1232.meaning: A telescope, as used to gaze at stars and planets in the night sky. Shown with an optical tube mounted on a tripod, positioned at various angles and generally depicted as metal.

1233.name: Satellite Antenna
1233.meaning: A dish antenna, as used to send or receive information to or from a communication satellite—or 👽 Extraterrestrial Life. Generally depicted as a mounted, metal dish with its antenna positioned at 45° to the upper right.

1234.name: Syringe
1234.meaning: A medical syringe, as used to administer a vaccine or draw blood. Generally depicted at a 45° angle with a needle to the upper right.

1235.name: Drop of Blood
1235.meaning: A red drop of blood. May be used to talk about bleeding, injury, blood donation, or menstruation.

1236.name: Pill
1236.meaning: A capsule of medicine. Generally depicted at a 45° angle, half red, half yellow. Commonly used for content concerning health, medicine, and related professions as well various types of drugs.

1237.name: Adhesive Bandage
1237.meaning: An adhesive bandage used for first aid. Sometimes called a Band-Aid or band aid after the trademarked product. Sometimes called a plaster.

1238.name: Stethoscope
1238.meaning: A stethoscope with a round resonator and two earpieces. Shown in black, blue, green, or red, depending on the platform.

1239.name: Door
1239.meaning: A door, as to the entrance of a room, house, or new opportunity. (We’ll see ourselves out 🚪🚶.) Depicted in brown, as made of wood, with a gold handle.

1240.name: Mirror
1240.meaning:
Mirror was approved as part of Unicode 13.0 in 2020
and added to Emoji 13.0 in 2020.

1241.name: Window
1241.meaning:
Window was approved as part of Unicode 13.0 in 2020
and added to Emoji 13.0 in 2020.

1242.name: Bed
1242.meaning: A bed, made up for sleeping in a house, hotel, or other sleeping accommodation. Shown with a headboard at the left, footboard, mattress, pillow, and sheet. Most platforms suggest a wooden frame and feature blue or red sheets.

1243.name: Couch and Lamp
1243.meaning: A couch (sofa) with a floor lamp on the right, as in the living room of a house. Color and style of the couch and lamp vary widely by platform. Used for various content concerning furniture and housing as well as resting and lounging.

1245.name: Toilet
1245.meaning: A white toilet, as used to deposit a 💩 Pile of Poo. (Don’t forget the 🧻 Roll of Paper.) Most platforms depict a porcelain toilet in profile, bowl facing to the left.

1246.name: Plunger
1246.meaning:
Plunger was approved as part of Unicode 13.0 in 2020
and added to Emoji 13.0 in 2020.

1247.name: Shower
1247.meaning: A silver shower head, streaming water to the left. Pressure level varies across platforms. 🧼 Soap not provided.

1248.name: Bathtub
1248.meaning: A white bathtub with a silver shower head. Often depicted as a cast-iron tub with claw-foot legs. Commonly used for various content concerning bathing, washing, cleaning, and bathrooms more generally.

1249.name: Mouse Trap
1249.meaning: A trap intended to catch a mouse, rat, or other unwanted rodent. Metaphorically used in emoji form to suggest any kind of trap or entrapment.

1250.name: Razor
1250.meaning: A straight razor or a safety razor, depicted in various colors across platforms.

1251.name: Lotion Bottle
1251.meaning: A bottle of lotion for the skin, such as moisturizer or sunscreen (sunblock). May be used for other hygienic liquids, including shampoo and body wash, as well as beauty products.

1252.name: Safety Pin
1252.meaning: A silver safety pin or clip, as used to fasten fabric. Generally shown clasped at a 45° angle, with its spring at the lower left.

1253.name: Broom
1253.meaning: A traditional broom, as used for sweeping—or ridden by a witch. Shown at a 45° angle, with a wooden handle and yellow bristles at the lower left.

1254.name: Basket
1254.meaning: A basket, as used for storing or carrying such things as food or clothes. Appearance widely varies across platforms but generally depicted as woven from wicker with one or more handles. Commonly used to represent doing laundry or having a picnic.

1255.name: Roll of Paper
1255.meaning: A roll of paper, as toilet paper (toilet tissue). May also be a roll of kitchen/paper towels. Depicted at various angles, with a sheet unfurling.

1256.name: Bucket
1256.meaning:
Bucket was approved as part of Unicode 13.0 in 2020
and added to Emoji 13.0 in 2020.

1257.name: Soap
1257.meaning: A bar of soap, as used in the shower, bath or for hand washing. Generally shown with lathered bubbles. Depicted in various colors, often pink, and at different angles.

1258.name: Toothbrush
1258.meaning:
Toothbrush was approved as part of Unicode 13.0 in 2020
and added to Emoji 13.0 in 2020.

1259.name: Sponge
1259.meaning: A peanut-shaped sponge, as used for cleaning or bathing. Generally depicted in yellow and at different angles across platforms. Commonly used for various content concerning bathing, washing, and cleaning.

1260.name: Fire Extinguisher
1260.meaning: A fire extinguisher, as used to put out small fires. Depicted as a red tank with a black hose and pressure gauge. Most platforms include an image of a flame on a white label.

1261.name: Shopping Cart
1261.meaning:
Shopping Cart was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016
under the name “Shopping Trolley”
and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

1262.name: Cigarette
1262.meaning: A lit, filtered cigarette, shown burning at different directions. Commonly used to represent various forms of smoking (e.g., tobacco, marijuana, vaping) as well as metaphorical senses of smoking.

1263.name: Coffin
1263.meaning: A traditional coffin, as used to bury the dead. Depicted at various angles as a closed, six-sided, wooden coffin, tapered at the head and foot with golden handles.

1264.name: Headstone
1264.meaning:
Headstone was approved as part of Unicode 13.0 in 2020
and added to Emoji 13.0 in 2020.

1265.name: Funeral Urn
1265.meaning: An urn, as used to hold the cremated ashes of the dead. Appearance varies, but generally depicted as a covered, bronze container with a rounded body and tapered foot.

1266.name: Moai
1266.meaning: A moai, one of the famed, giant stone statues of human figures on Easter Island. Depicted as a gray stone carving of a stylized human head with a prominent brow and nose, most often facing left.

1267.name: Placard
1267.meaning: A sign on a post, commonly seen to promote ideas, causes, or commercial advertising. Often used in political advertising "lawn sign" or in protest.

1268.name: Potable Water
1268.meaning: A symbol for potable (drinkable) water, usually shown with a faucet filling a drinking glass. Commonly used for various content concerning water, drinking, thirst, and dripping.

1269.name: Heart with Arrow
1269.meaning: A heart emoji with an arrow through the center, like the arrow that cupid shoots for love.

1270.name: Heart with Ribbon
1270.meaning: A heart-shaped box, tied with a ribbon. May be a gift box, box of chocolates, or a jewellery box.

1271.name: Sparkling Heart
1271.meaning: A pink love heart with stars around it, making it look like it is sparkling or shimmering.

1272.name: Growing Heart
1272.meaning: A pink heart, inside a slightly larger pink heart, inside a larger-again pink heart. Intended to give the impression of a heart increasing in size.

1273.name: Beating Heart
1273.meaning: A heart with vibration / movement lines above it, indicating it is a beating heart. Displayed in pink or red on most platforms, this emoji is intended to be used as a beating heart representing either life, or love.

1274.name: Revolving Hearts
1274.meaning: Hearts revolving around one or more other hearts. This emoji was originally animated on a number of Japanese devices.

1275.name: Two Hearts
1275.meaning: Two pink love hearts. One larger than the other. Can be used to display that “love is in the air”.

1276.name: Heart Decoration
1276.meaning: A decorative heart that displays on Apple devices as a white heart-shaped cutout in a pink or purple roundrect.

1277.name: Heart Exclamation
1277.meaning: A decorative exclamation mark, where a heart forms the top part of the symbol, and a circle the lower part. Similar to the way to the man in business suit levitating also creates a similar shape.

1278.name: Broken Heart
1278.meaning: A love heart, broken in two. This emoji represents the aching one feels when they are missing the person they love.

1279.name: Red Heart
1279.meaning: A classic red love heart emoji, used for expressions of love and romance. This is the most popular heart emoji A similar emoji exists for the heart suit in a deck of playing cards.

1280.name: Orange Heart
1280.meaning:
Orange Heart was approved as part of Unicode 10.0 in 2017
and added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017.

1281.name: Yellow Heart
1281.meaning: A yellow or gold colored love-heart, frequently used alongside other colored hearts. This displayed as a pink hairy heart on Android 4.4.

1282.name: Green Heart
1282.meaning: A green heart emoji, often used alongside other colored hearts. Frequently used on Twitter in reference to Korean boy band NCT.

1283.name: Blue Heart
1283.meaning: A blue heart emoji, commonly used by brands as a neutral heart color.

1284.name: Purple Heart
1284.meaning: A purple heart emoji, often used alongside other colored hearts. Frequently used on Twitter in reference to Korean boy band Bangtan Sonyeondan, more commonly known as BTS.

1285.name: Brown Heart
1285.meaning: A brown heart, often used discuss topics related to racial identity 🧑🏽🧑🏾🧑🏿

1286.name: Black Heart
1286.meaning: A heart shaded completely black. May be used to express morbidity, sorrow, or a form of dark humor, but despite the color remains most commonly used for love and affection.

1287.name: White Heart
1287.meaning: A white heart emoji, used for love and affection. Also commonly used to discuss someone passing away.

1288.name: Hundred Points
1288.meaning: 100 emoji: the number one-hundred, written in red, underlined twice for emphasis.

1289.name: Anger Symbol
1289.meaning: A red symbol found in Anime/Manga and used to represent the veins popping on a very angry person.

1290.name: Speech Balloon
1290.meaning: A cartoon-style balloon used to represent spoken word in comics. Sometimes  used in communication apps to indicate that another person is typing a message.

1291.name: Eye in Speech Bubble
1291.meaning: A speech bubble showing an eye inside. When using text-to-speech on Apple platforms, this emoji is read aloud as: "Eye in speech bubble representing anti-bullying campaign". This emoji was released in conjunction with the Ad Council for the I Am A Witness campaign.

1292.name: Left Speech Bubble
1292.meaning: A left-facing speech bubble, which was included in Unicode 7.0, but not considered a standard addition for the purposes of emoji presentation.

1293.name: Right Anger Bubble
1293.meaning: A form of speech balloon used with angular edges, used to denote angry speech in comics.

1294.name: Thought Balloon
1294.meaning: A large cloud-like shape more commonly known as a thought bubble.

1295.name: Zzz
1295.meaning: A series of three Zs making a Zzz. Represents sleeping, snoring, dreaming, or any sleep-related state. Can also be used in some contexts to represent something that is boring.

1296.name: White Flower
1296.meaning: A stylized white flower. Generally depicted as a rosette-shaped cherry blossom in pink or red outline, often with a white fill.

1297.name: Hot Springs
1297.meaning: Representation of hot springs with steam rising from a circular tub. This is the common symbol used to represent an onsen on maps in Japan.

1298.name: Barber Pole
1298.meaning: A pole spiraled with red, white, and blue stripes, as spins out front of a barbershop. Commonly used for various content concerning haircutting and hairstyling.

1299.name: Stop Sign
1299.meaning: A red, octagonal sign. Used in many countries as a stop sign.

1324.name: Cyclone
1324.meaning: An icon used to represent a cyclone. Some versions of this emoji show a spiral shape, which may be used for decorative purposes.

1325.name: Spade Suit
1325.meaning: A spade symbol emoji, which is used in card games for the spades suit.

1326.name: Heart Suit
1326.meaning: A heart symbol emoji, used in card games for the hearts suit. In emoji form, this is most commonly used for love, affectiction, romance and positive intentions. Sometimes shown in a slightly darker shade of red than ❤️ Red Heart.

1327.name: Diamond Suit
1327.meaning: A diamond symbol emoji, which is used in card games for the diamonds suit.

1328.name: Club Suit
1328.meaning: A club symbol emoji, which is used in card games for the clubs suit.

1329.name: Joker
1329.meaning: The joker in a deck of cards, usually appearing like a court jester.

1330.name: Mahjong Red Dragon
1330.meaning: The red dragon tile in the game of Japanese Mahjong. White, with red 中 character printed on it.

1331.name: Flower Playing Cards
1331.meaning: A type of cards known as hanafuda cards in Japan which are used for a range of different games that require associating pictures (there are no numbers on the cards).

1332.name: Muted Speaker
1332.meaning: A speaker with a red line through it, indicating muted volume or silencing of audio.

1333.name: Speaker Low Volume
1333.meaning: A speaker cone displayed without any sound waves.

1334.name: Speaker Medium Volume
1334.meaning: A speaker cone displayed with one sound wave, generally used as an icon to indicate the decreasing of volume on a phone or computer.

1335.name: Speaker High Volume
1335.meaning: A speaker cone displayed with three sound waves, generally used as an icon to indicate the increasing of volume on a phone or computer.

1336.name: Loudspeaker
1336.meaning: A loudspeaker used to make announcements in public areas such as schools, or sporting grounds.

1337.name: Megaphone
1337.meaning:
Megaphone was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Cheering Megaphone”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1338.name: Postal Horn
1338.meaning: A postal horn (post horn). Depicted as a coiled, valveless, brass horn, like a bugle or trumpet, with two red tassels. Sometimes used to mark announcements as well as for various content concerning brass instruments, music, or mail.

1339.name: Bell
1339.meaning: A gold or yellow bell, which is commonly used on mobile phones as an icon for notifications or ringing sounds.

1340.name: Bell with Slash
1340.meaning: A gold or yellow bell with a red line through it, which is commonly used on mobile phones as an icon for the silencing of notifications or ringing sounds. A mute, or silent mode.

1341.name: Musical Note
1341.meaning: A music note emoji, which can denote song lyrics, or other music related topics.

1342.name: Musical Notes
1342.meaning: Three eighth notes (quavers in British English), used to represent music or singing. Sometimes inserted next to quoted lyrics, to make it clear that they are part of a song.

1343.name: Chart Increasing with Yen
1343.meaning: A graph showing the value of the Japanese Yen rising.

1344.name: Elevator
1344.meaning:
Elevator was approved as part of Unicode 13.0 in 2020
and added to Emoji 13.0 in 2020.

1345.name: ATM Sign
1345.meaning:
ATM Sign was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Automated Teller Machine”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1346.name: Litter in Bin Sign
1346.meaning: A symbol showing a person putting litter (rubbish) in the trash (rubbish bin). A more positive version of the Do Not Litter Symbol.

1347.name: Potable Water
1347.meaning: A symbol for potable (drinkable) water, usually shown with a faucet filling a drinking glass. Commonly used for various content concerning water, drinking, thirst, and dripping.

1348.name: Wheelchair Symbol
1348.meaning: The international symbol of access, used to denote a facility which has been designed with accessibility or people in wheelchairs in mind. Appears as a blue sign, with a white graphic of a person sitting in a wheelchair.

1349.name: Men’s Room
1349.meaning: A stick-figure icon of a man, generally used to indicate a male restroom. The female equivalent is the Womens Symbol emoji.

1350.name: Women’s Room
1350.meaning: A stick-figure icon of a woman, generally used to indicate a female restroom. The male equivalent is the Mens Symbol emoji.

1351.name: Restroom
1351.meaning: A restroom symbol, depicting a iconography of a man and woman. Used to indicate the location of public bathrooms / toilets / restrooms.

1352.name: Baby Symbol
1352.meaning: The symbol for a baby, usually used to indicate a room that is suitable to change a baby in. Often located in or near public restrooms.

1353.name: Water Closet
1353.meaning: A water closet is a name used for public toilet, bathroom or restroom used in some countries. Typically abbreviated to the letters WC, this may be found on signage in public buildings, as an alternative to the restroom symbol.

1354.name: Warning
1354.meaning: A triangle with an exclamation mark inside, used as a warning or alert.

1355.name: Children Crossing
1355.meaning: A crossing sign for children, usually positioned near schools or other areas that drivers should be cautious of young children in the area.

1356.name: No Entry
1356.meaning:
No Entry was approved as part of Unicode 5.2 in 2009
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1357.name: Prohibited
1357.meaning: A red circle with a diagonal line through the middle, from top-left to bottom right, used to indicate that something is not permitted

1358.name: No Bicycles
1358.meaning: A bicycle with a red stroke through it, indicating that bikes are prohibited from this location.

1359.name: No Smoking
1359.meaning:
No Smoking was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “No Smoking Symbol”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1360.name: No Littering
1360.meaning: A person dropping litter (rubbish, trash) with a red stroke through it, indicating that littering is prohibited in this area.

1361.name: Non-Potable Water
1361.meaning: A water tap with a red stroke through it, indicating that water is not safe for drinking (non-potable).

1362.name: No Pedestrians
1362.meaning: A pedestrian symbol with a red stroke through it, indicating that pedestrians are prohibited from this location.

1363.name: No Mobile Phones
1363.meaning: A mobile phone with a red stroke through it, indicating that mobile phones should not be present. Often seen in restricted areas, such as Customs or Passport Control.

1364.name: No One Under Eighteen
1364.meaning: The number eighteen with a red stroke through it, indicating a location where a person must be aged 18 or above to enter. Often used online to indicate adult or NSFW content.

1365.name: Radioactive
1365.meaning: A hazard symbol for radiation or radioactivity. May appear similar to a three-pronged fan at small sizes.

1366.name: Biohazard
1366.meaning:
Biohazard was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993
under the name “Biohazard Sign”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1368.name: Up-Right Arrow
1368.meaning: An arrow pointing diagonally in an up-right, or north-east direction.

1370.name: Down-Right Arrow
1370.meaning: An arrow pointing diagonally in an down-right, or south-east direction.

1372.name: Down-Left Arrow
1372.meaning: An arrow pointing diagonally in an down-left, or south-west direction.

1374.name: Up-Left Arrow
1374.meaning: An arrow pointing diagonally in an up-left, or north-west direction.

1375.name: Up-Down Arrow
1375.meaning: A vertical line with arrowheads on both ends, pointing up and down.

1376.name: Left-Right Arrow
1376.meaning: A horizontal line with arrowheads on both ends, pointing left and right.

1377.name: Right Arrow Curving Left
1377.meaning: An arrow pointing to the left, with a curved hook at the other end. Similar in appearance to a sideways U Turn symbol, or a reply icon in an email application.

1378.name: Left Arrow Curving Right
1378.meaning: An arrow pointing to the right, with a curved hook at the other end. Similar in appearance to a sideways U Turn symbol, or a forward icon in an email application.

1381.name: Clockwise Vertical Arrows
1381.meaning:
Clockwise Vertical Arrows was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Clockwise Downwards and Upwards Open Circle Arrows”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1382.name: Counterclockwise Arrows Button
1382.meaning: Two arrows forming a circle, pointing in an anticlockwise direction. Similar to symbols sometimes used for refresh or rotate. May also be used to indicate a task is in progress.

1383.name: Back Arrow
1383.meaning:
Back Arrow was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Back with Leftwards Arrow Above”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1384.name: End Arrow
1384.meaning:
End Arrow was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “End with Leftwards Arrow Above”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1385.name: On! Arrow
1385.meaning:
On! Arrow was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “On with Exclamation Mark with Left Right Arrow Above”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1386.name: Soon Arrow
1386.meaning: The word "soon" with an arrow above it, pointing to the right.

1387.name: Top Arrow
1387.meaning: The word "top" with an arrow pointing up above it.

1388.name: Place of Worship
1388.meaning: A building used for worship by people of any faith or religion. Examples include a church, mosque, or synagogue. A person is shown on their knees praying, in this symbol.

1389.name: Atom Symbol
1389.meaning:
Atom Symbol was approved as part of Unicode 4.1 in 2005
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1390.name: Om
1390.meaning: A symbol often used in relation to the religions of Hinduism, Buddhism, Sikhism and Jainism.

1391.name: Star of David
1391.meaning: A symbol often used in relation to the religion of Judaism. Not to be confused with the Six Pointed Star With Middle Dot emoji.

1392.name: Wheel of Dharma
1392.meaning: A symbol often used in relation to the Indian religions of Hinduism, Buddhism, Sikhism and Jainism.

1393.name: Yin Yang
1393.meaning:
Yin Yang was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1394.name: Latin Cross
1394.meaning: A latin cross, otherwise known as a Christian cross. This cross symbol is often used as a symbol of Christianity. Similar in appearance to the Orthodox cross.

1395.name: Orthodox Cross
1395.meaning:
Orthodox Cross was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1396.name: Star and Crescent
1396.meaning: The crescent moon and star is a symbol often associated with the religion of Islam. This symbol can be found on the flags of many countries, such as Algeria, Azerbaijan, Malaysia, Pakistan and Turkey.

1397.name: Peace Symbol
1397.meaning: A circular symbol, commonly used as a representation of peace. Alternatives include the Victory Hand, or the Dove of Peace.

1398.name: Menorah
1398.meaning: A menorah showing nine lit candles, used on the Jewish holiday of Hanukkah.

1399.name: Dotted Six-Pointed Star
1399.meaning: A star with six points, and a dot in the center. Similar to the Star of David emoji.

1400.name: Aries
1400.meaning: The Aries astrological sign in the Zodiac. This Zodiac Symbol represents a Ram.

1401.name: Taurus
1401.meaning: The Taurus astrological sign in the Zodiac. This Zodiac Symbol represents a Bull.

1402.name: Gemini
1402.meaning: The Gemini astrological sign in the Zodiac. This Zodiac Symbol represents Twins.

1403.name: Cancer
1403.meaning: The Cancer astrological sign in the Zodiac. This Zodiac Symbol represents a Crab.

1404.name: Leo
1404.meaning: The Leo astrological sign in the Zodiac. This Zodiac Symbol represents a Lion.

1405.name: Virgo
1405.meaning: The Virgo astrological sign in the Zodiac. This Zodiac Symbol represents a Maiden.

1406.name: Libra
1406.meaning: The Libra astrological sign in the Zodiac. This Zodiac Symbol represents weighing scales.

1407.name: Scorpio
1407.meaning: The Scorpius astrological sign in the Zodiac. This Zodiac Symbol represents a Scorpion.

1408.name: Sagittarius
1408.meaning: The Sagittarius astrological sign in the Zodiac. This Zodiac Symbol represents an Archer.

1409.name: Capricorn
1409.meaning: The Capricorn astrological sign in the Zodiac. This Zodiac Symbol represents a Goat.

1410.name: Aquarius
1410.meaning: The Aquarius astrological sign in the Zodiac. This Zodiac Symbol represents a Water-bearer.

1411.name: Pisces
1411.meaning: The Pisces astrological sign in the Zodiac. This Zodiac Symbol represents a Fish.

1412.name: Ophiuchus
1412.meaning: Ophiuchus is used by some as a 13th sign in the Zodiac. The symbol for ophiuchus appears a U shape with a wavy line through it.

1413.name: Shuffle Tracks Button
1413.meaning: Two arrows pointing right while crossing over one another. Used to indicate putting music on shuffle: randomizing the order of tracks in the upcoming playlist. May also be used to indicate two items switching places.

1414.name: Repeat Button
1414.meaning: Circular arrows pointing in a clockwise direction. Used in music player applications to loop a track or album continuously. Commonly used to repesent a retweet on Twitter.

1415.name: Repeat Single Button
1415.meaning: Arrows pointing in a clockwise direction, with a number 1 badge in the lower corner.  Used in music player applications to loop a track or album once.

1416.name: Play Button
1416.meaning: A triangle-shaped arrow, pointing right. Commonly used as a symbol for play.

1417.name: Fast-Forward Button
1417.meaning: Two triangles pointing to the right. Most commonly used as a symbol for fast forwarding media such as video tapes, CDs, or digital audio and video.

1418.name: Next Track Button
1418.meaning: A symbol used in media players to indicate skipping to the next track (or scene). Shown as two triangles pointing right followed by a vertical bar.

1419.name: Play or Pause Button
1419.meaning: A play-pause icon, showing a right-pointing triangle (play) next to a double vertical bar (pause).

1421.name: Fast Reverse Button
1421.meaning: Two triangles pointing to the left. Most commonly used as a symbol for rewinding media such as video tapes, CDs, or digital audio and video.

1422.name: Last Track Button
1422.meaning: A symbol used in media players to indicate skipping to the first or previous track (or scene). Shown as a vertical bar followed by two triangles pointing left.

1423.name: Upwards Button
1423.meaning: A triangle-shaped arrow, pointing up. Styled similarly to the left and right pointing triangles on iOS, but shown in red on Windows, and orange on Android.

1424.name: Fast Up Button
1424.meaning: Two triangles pointing up. Similar to rewind icon, rotated 90° clockwise.

1425.name: Downwards Button
1425.meaning: A triangle-shaped arrow, pointing down. Styled similarly to the left and right pointing triangles on iOS, but shown in red on Windows, and orange on Android.

1426.name: Fast Down Button
1426.meaning: Two triangles pointing down. Similar to rewind icon, rotated 90° counter-clockwise.

1427.name: Pause Button
1427.meaning: A pause icon, displayed as two vertical bars.

1428.name: Stop Button
1428.meaning: A stop icon, displayed as a square.

1429.name: Record Button
1429.meaning: A record icon, displayed as a circle.

1430.name: Eject Button
1430.meaning: An eject symbol, displayed as an upward-pointing triangle above a horiztonal bar. May be used as a physical button or an icon in a user interface. Represents the action of ejecting physical media such as a floppy disk, videocasette or DVD on a computer or media player.

1431.name: Cinema
1431.meaning: An emoji representing the cinema: a large screen showing the latest movies, available to the public. Displayed by most platforms as a film projector symbol, and previously by Google and Microsoft as a cinema screen with curtains.

1432.name: Dim Button
1432.meaning: An icon of a outlined sun, used when decreasing the brightness of a screen. Appears smaller than the High Brightness Symbol.

1433.name: Bright Button
1433.meaning: An icon of a outlined sun, used when increasing the brightness of a screen. Appears larger than the Low Brightness Symbol.

1434.name: Antenna Bars
1434.meaning: Bars increasing in height, showing the strength of the mobile (cellular) phone signal. More bars signifies better reception.

1435.name: Vibration Mode
1435.meaning: An icon representing vibration mode on a mobile phone, indicating that a phone should be switched to silent and/or vibrate mode.

1436.name: Mobile Phone Off
1436.meaning: A sign indicating that mobile phones should be turned off. Used in situations such as a cinema or live performance.

1437.name: Female Sign
1437.meaning: A circle shown with a crossed vertical line beneath it, used as a representation for women. Often used on International Women's Day.

1438.name: Male Sign
1438.meaning: A circle shown with a diagonal arrow pointing out the top-right, used as a representation for men.

1439.name: Multiply
1439.meaning:
Multiply was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993
under the name “Heavy Multiplication X”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1443.name: Infinity
1443.meaning: The symbol for infinity enclosed within a circle or square.

1444.name: Double Exclamation Mark
1444.meaning:

1445.name: Exclamation Question Mark

1447.name: White Question Mark

1448.name: White Exclamation Mark

1449.name: Exclamation Mark
1449.meaning:
Exclamation Mark was approved as part of Unicode 5.2 in 2009

1450.name: Wavy Dash
1450.meaning: Just like a regular dash (hyphen), sometimes used in Asian character sets in the same way a – or — is used in latin character sets.

1451.name: Currency Exchange
1451.meaning: A symbol for exchanging of two currencies. Most commonly displayed as a dollar symbol, with arrows to and from a yen symbol.

1452.name: Heavy Dollar Sign
1452.meaning:
Heavy Dollar Sign was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1453.name: Medical Symbol
1453.meaning: A symbol displaying of a rod with a snake entwined around the outside in a downward-spiral shape.

1454.name: Recycling Symbol
1454.meaning: The universal recycling symbol, featuring three arrows pointing clockwise in a triangular formation.

1455.name: Fleur-de-lis
1455.meaning: A decorative symbol that appears like a golden flower, but found in all manner of logos, symbols, and patterns. This symbol forms part of the World Scout Emblem, amongst other uses.

1456.name: Trident Emblem
1456.meaning: A trident is a three-pronged spear, that appears similar to a pitchfork. Often held by Greek or Roman Gods in statues.

1457.name: Name Badge
1457.meaning: A name badge, used to identify oneself in a location that others may not know your name, such as a school trip, or a work conference.

1458.name: Japanese Symbol for Beginner
1458.meaning: A yellow and green shield symbol, called a Shoshinsha Mark. Must be displayed by drivers in Japan for one year after they receive their drivers licence.

1459.name: Hollow Red Circle
1459.meaning: Used as an alternative to a check (tick) in Japan for a something that is correct. The opposite of an X (cross mark) for something wrong.

1460.name: Check Mark Button
1460.meaning: A check mark that displays with a white outlined appearance. Shows on most platforms with a bright green rounded rectangle or circle surrounding it.

1461.name: Check Box with Check
1461.meaning: A checkbox showing a check mark inside the box. Not to be confused with the similarly named Ballot Box With Ballot emoji.

1462.name: Check Mark
1462.meaning: A thick check mark / tick displayed on some platforms in a handwritten style. Generally displayed in black, except on Windows where it is displayed in green. Commonly used in lists to signify completed tasks or verification of a statement of fact.

1463.name: Cross Mark
1463.meaning: A large red cross mark, displayed in the shape of a letter X and similar to a multiplication sign.

1464.name: Cross Mark Button
1464.meaning:
Cross Mark Button was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Negative Squared Cross Mark”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1465.name: Curly Loop
1465.meaning: A curled loop, which is shown in black on most platforms. Displayed as a blue ribbon on Samsung devices.

1466.name: Double Curly Loop
1466.meaning: Two curly loops, which represent a reel-to-reel tape recorder. Used as a symbol for voicemail on many phones.

1467.name: Part Alternation Mark
1467.meaning: Used in traditional Japanese music such as Noh or Renga, to indicate the start of a song. More specifically, the part alternation mark is displayed where the singer’s part begins.

1468.name: Eight-Spoked Asterisk
1468.meaning: Used in a similar manner to a regular * asterisk character but tends to be shown in a similar vertical alignment to a • bullet point. The eight spoked asterisk has both a ✳︎ text and ✳️ emoji presentation available on most platforms.

1469.name: Eight-Pointed Star
1469.meaning: A star with eight points, that is commonly shown in orange, and for some reason, with only four points.

1470.name: Sparkle
1470.meaning: Used a decorative bullet-point, the sparkle has both a ❇︎ text and ❇️ emoji presentation available on most platforms.

1471.name: Copyright
1471.meaning:
Copyright was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993
under the name “Copyright Sign”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1472.name: Registered
1472.meaning:
Registered was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993
under the name “Registered Sign”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1473.name: Trade Mark
1473.meaning: A trademark symbol, the letters TM displayed after a word that is trademarked.

1474.name: Keycap Number Sign
1474.meaning: A hash key, sometimes referred to as a pound key in the United States. Most commonly used online to make a hashtag (or hash flag) on social media sites.

1475.name: Keycap Asterisk
1475.meaning:
The Keycap Asterisk emoji is a keycap sequence combining * Asterisk and ⃣ Combining Enclosing Keycap.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

1476.meaning:
The Keycap Digit Zero emoji is a keycap sequence combining 0 Digit Zero and ⃣ Combining Enclosing Keycap.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

1485.name: Keycap Digit Nine

1486.name: Keycap: 10
1486.meaning: The number 10 on a square with rounded corners, designed to look like a keycap.

1487.name: Input Latin Uppercase
1487.meaning: A symbol showing the capital letters A, B, C and D. Intended to be used on a software keyboard, or other input screen to toggle capital letter input.

1488.name: Input Latin Lowercase
1488.meaning: A symbol showing the lowercase letters a, b, c and d. Intended to be used on a software keyboard, or other input screen to toggle lowercase letter input.

1489.name: Input Numbers
1489.meaning: A symbol showing the numbers 1, 2, 3 and 4. Intended to be used on a software keyboard, or other input screen to enable symbol input, as opposed to alphabetical or symbol input.

1490.name: Input Symbols
1490.meaning: A symbol showing the following glyphs: 〒 (Japanese postal mark), 𝅘𝅥𝅮 (music note), & (ampersand, or sometimes an @ symbol) and % (percentage sign).

1491.name: Input Latin Letters
1491.meaning: A symbol showing the lowercase letters a, b, c and d. Intended to be used on a software keyboard, or other input screen to enable alphabetical input, as opposed to numeric or symbol input.

1492.name: A Button (Blood Type)
1492.meaning: A symbol representing Blood Type A. Displayed as the letter A on a red background.

1493.name: AB Button (Blood Type)
1493.meaning: A symbol representing Blood Type AB. Displayed as the letters AB on a red background.

1494.name: B Button (Blood Type)
1494.meaning: A symbol representing Blood Type B. Displayed as the letter B on a red background.

1495.name: CL Button
1495.meaning: CL is what shows on the CLear button of some older mobile phones.

1496.name: Cool Button
1496.meaning: The word cool, shown enclosed in a square. This generally displays in a shade of blue, or blue-gray on most platforms. Used as a text decoration.

1497.name: Free Button
1497.meaning: The word free, shown enclosed in a square.

1498.name: Information
1498.meaning: A lowercase letter i, enclosed in a rounded square or circle. Implemented in apps or websites to indicate that help or further information is available.

1499.name: ID Button
1499.meaning: The letters ID in a square.

1500.name: Circled M
1500.meaning: The letter M in a circle, commonly used in to identify a Metro (subway, underground train) station in a city area.

1501.name: New Button
1501.meaning: The word new, shown enclosed in a square.

1502.name: NG Button
1502.meaning: The letters NG, shown enclosed in a square, which are an acronym for the words No Good.

1503.name: O Button (Blood Type)
1503.meaning: A symbol representing Blood Type O. Displayed as the letter O on a red background.

1504.name: OK Button
1504.meaning: The letters OK, shown enclosed in a square. Meaning Okay, denoting approval. The opposite of the Squared NG Emoji.

1505.name: P Button
1505.meaning:
P Button was approved as part of Unicode 5.2 in 2009
under the name “Negative Squared Latin Capital Letter P”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1506.name: SOS Button
1506.meaning: SOS is the description for the distress signal in Morse Code. This emoji means SOS or “emergency”.

1507.name: Up! Button
1507.meaning: The word up with an exclamation point after it, shown enclosed in a square. Originally intended to denote leveling up in a game.

1508.name: Vs Button
1508.meaning:
Vs Button was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Squared Vs”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1509.name: Japanese “Here” Button
1509.meaning: Means “Here” in Japanese, referring to a destination.

1510.name: Japanese “Service Charge” Button
1510.meaning: Translates as meaning complimentary, or free of charge. For example, a drink that is given "on the house" to a regular customer.

1511.name: Japanese “Monthly Amount” Button
1511.meaning: CJK Ideographs are characters used in Chinese, Japanese and Korean languages. Their writing systems all completely or partly use Chinese characters.

1512.name: Japanese “Not Free of Charge” Button
1512.meaning: This emoji means to own or posses.

1513.name: Japanese “Reserved” Button
1513.meaning: This character translates as meaning a finger or toe pointing to indicate a certain direction.

1515.name: Japanese “Discount” Button
1515.meaning: Symbol for a sale, or bargain prices in Japan (“cut prices”). Literally translated, this character means to cut or divide.

1516.name: Japanese “Free of Charge” Button
1516.meaning: This means to lack, or have none of something.

1517.name: Japanese “Prohibited” Button
1517.meaning: This Emoji means “prohibit, restrict or forbid” in Japanese.

1518.name: Japanese “Acceptable” Button
1518.meaning:
Japanese “Acceptable” Button was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Circled Ideograph Accept”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1520.name: Japanese “Passing Grade” Button
1520.meaning: Means “agreement” in Japanese. More literally, it means to unite, or join together.

1521.name: Japanese “Vacancy” Button
1521.meaning: This 空 character means empty and available in Japanese. This is used in the context of an empty parking space or a vacant hotel room.

1522.name: Japanese “Congratulations” Button
1522.meaning: Translated from Japanese, this means "congratulations" or "pray for happiness".

1523.name: Japanese “Secret” Button
1523.meaning:
Japanese “Secret” Button was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993
under the name “Circled Ideograph Secret”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1524.name: Japanese “Open for Business” Button
1524.meaning: Means “work” in Japanese.  This Emoji used to mean “open for business” and precedes business hours.

1525.name: Japanese “No Vacancy” Button
1525.meaning: This emoji means “full” in Japanese, usually used to denote “full capacity” such as a gas/petrol tank on a car or pre-paid phone card.

1534.name: White Circle

1535.name: Red Square
1535.meaning: A square shown in the color red. May be used to represent anything red, including a red penalty card in football (soccer).

1536.name: Orange Square
